04585nam a22005295i 9780774855525DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082007xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748555257 a10.59962/97807748555252doi  a(DE-B1597)662222  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.E7bK95 2007eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a333.95/49097191 aKulchyski, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKiumajut (Talking Back) :bGame Management and Inuit Rights, 1900-70 /cFrank James Tester, Peter Kulchyski. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps, Figures, and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tManaging the Game -- tTrapping and Trading: The Regulation of Inuit Hunting Prior to World War II -- tSagluniit (“Lies”): Manufacturing a Caribou Crisis -- tSugsaunngittugulli (“We Are Useless”¹): Surveying the Animals -- tWho Counts? Challenging Science and the Law -- tTalking Back -- tInuit Rights and Government Policy -- tBaker Lake, 1957: The Eskimo Council -- tInuit Petition for Their Rights -- tConclusion: Contested Ground -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKiumajut [Talking Back]: Game Management and Inuit Rights 1900-70 examines Inuit relations with the Canadian state, with a particular focus on two interrelated issues. The first is how a deeply flawed set of scientific practices for counting animal populations led policymakers to develop policies and laws intended to curtail the activities of Inuit hunters. Animal management informed by this knowledge became a justification for attempts to educate and, ultimately, to regulate Inuit hunters. The second issue is Inuit responses to the emerging regime of government intervention. The authors look closely at resulting court cases and rulings, as well as Inuit petitions. The activities of the first Inuit community council are also examined in exploring how Inuit began to "talk back" to the Canadian state. The authors' award-winning previous collaboration, Tammarniit [Mistakes]: Inuit Relocation in the Eastern Arctic 1939-63, focused on government responsibility, social welfare, and relocation in Inuit relations with the state. Kiumajut is not a continuation of Tammarniit, but rather an interrelated, stand-alone study that examines a separate range of issues relevant to a historical understanding of community development in Nunavut. Kiumajut draws on new material compiled from archival sources and from an archive of oral interviews conducted by the authors with Inuit elders and others between 1997 and 1999. This volume provides the reader with new and important insights for understanding this critical period in the history of Inuit in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aTester, Frank James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485552540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855525423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855525/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Col